    "type": "targeted_grid",
    "name": "oracle_validation_lite",
    "description": "Oracle validation sweep \u2014 tests the three literature-grounded price oracle proposals against the baseline oracle.\nProposals:\n  1. EMA lag on economic weight (Kristoufek 2015) \u2014 smooths early chop\n  2. Sigmoid factor mapping (Biais et al. 2019/Metcalfe) \u2014 nonlinear at extremes\n  3. Asymmetric cost-of-production price floor (Hayes 2019) \u2014 floors minority fork\n\nRun TWICE simultaneously on different namespaces to compare oracle behaviors for the same scenario grid:\n\n  Sweep A \u2014 baseline oracle:\n    python 3_run_sweep.py \\\n      --input oracle_validation_lite/build_manifest.json \\\n      --namespace sweep-oracle-a \\\n      --results-dir oracle_validation_lite/results_baseline \\\n      --duration 3000 --retarget-interval 144 --interval 2\n\n  Sweep B \u2014 all proposals enabled:\n    python 3_run_sweep.py \\\n      --input oracle_validation_lite/build_manifest.json \\\n      --namespace sweep-oracle-b \\\n      --results-dir oracle_validation_lite/results_proposals \\\n      --duration 3000 --retarget-interval 144 --interval 2 \\\n      --use-economic-ema --use-sigmoid --use-cost-floor\n\nThree economic_split values cover the known outcome zones:\n  0.35 \u2192 v26 expected to win (economic majority on v26 side)\n  0.60 \u2192 contested / narrow v27 advantage\n  0.82 \u2192 v27 expected to win (strong economic majority on v27 side)\n\nKey questions:\n  - Does EMA smooth the early price chop seen at t<300s?\n  - Does the sigmoid change the cascade threshold (econ=0.60 flip)?\n  - Does the cost floor affect pricing when one fork has minority hashrate?\n\nUses 144-block retarget for fast feedback (multiple retarget cycles in 3000s). Lite network (25 nodes) keeps runtime short \u2014 ~3000s per scenario.\n",
    "spec_file": "specs/oracle_validation_lite.yaml",
